PROGRESS MEMO 1:

This dataset includes 257,912 observations and 17 variables containing both numerical (location (coordinates), date, case number, etc.) and categorical variables (primary description (type of crime), secondary description (weapons used), block where the crime was committed, etc). There are 6 numerical variables and 11 categorical. With the amount of data, there are many relationships to be explored in this dataset.

Why this data

I chose this data because I was curious to learn more about crime rates in Chicago and explore trends within the dataset, also considering we are located close to the city.

Although I am still narrowing it down, I am interested exploring the correlation between types of crimes committed and another variable, possibly location or date of occurrence of the crime in Chicago. Since I am sure I want to explore the type of crime vs another variable, in Figure 1 I explored the distribution of the types of crimes committed in Chicago.

Data quality & complexity check

This data was collected by the City of Chicago during a specific time period5. Data is extracted from the Chicago Police Departmentâs CLEAR (Citizen Law Enforcement Analysis and Reporting) system and is a reputable source of information, other than room for bias of police officers who collected the data. This is something I will have to note while making conclusions about the data.

5Â one year prior to current date minus the past 7 days

6Â as seen in Figure 1

This dataset is updated daily, Tuesday through Sunday. This dataset is complex considering the number of variables and distribution of types of crime6 and that there are 6 variables with missing data, as shown in Figure 2 and Table 1.

Potential data issues

One issue with the data mentioned earlier is that the police officers who collected it are subject to bias, which could be reflected in the data by representing potentially harmful stereotypes and generalizations. Considering crime is a complex and sensitive topic to explore, many incorrect assumptions can be made without proper consideration of the influence of bias.

Another possible issue is missingness in the data, since there are 1589 values in total missing in the dataset as seen in Table 1. The missing data is important if I decide to focus on the relationship between type of crimes committed and location, as the variables with missing data are x-coordinate, y-coordinate, latitude and longitude, location, and location description. The exact counts are shown in Table 1 and the variables all explore the location where the crime occurred.

This indicates it may be ideal to explore a variable other than location, such as date or number of arrests, and its relation to the type of crime. In Figure 1, I explored the distribution of the types of crimes using the primary_description variable.
